abstract = {We use Kepler K2 Campaign 4 short-cadence photometry to measure white light flares in the young, moving group brown dwarfs 2MASS J03350208+2342356 (2M0335+23) and 2MASS J03552337+1133437 (2M0355+11), and report on long-cadence photometry of a flare in the Pleiades M8 brown dwarf CFHT-PL-17. We also report a new measurement of the radial velocity of 2M0335+23 which confirms that this M7 brown dwarf is a beta Pic Moving Group member. We identify a long-lived starspot, and find that the rotation period (5.24 hr) and projected rotational velocity (45 km/s) confirm 2M0335+23 is inflated ({\$}R \backslashge 0.20 R{\_}\backslashodot{\$}) as predicted. We detect 22 white light flares on 2M0335+23. The flare frequency distribution follows a power-law distribution with slope {\$}-\backslashalpha = -1.7{\$} over the range {\$}10{\^{}}{\{}31{\}}{\$} to {\$}10{\^{}}{\{}33{\}}{\$} erg. This slope is similar to that observed in the Sun and warmer flare stars, and with lower energy flares in previous ground-based work on M6-M8 field very-low-mass stars; taken the two datasets together, the flare frequency distribution for young brown dwarfs is a power law over 4.3 orders of magnitude. Even more energetic flares are possible on warm brown dwarfs, as demonstrated by the superflare on the 130-Myr old CFHT-PL-17, which we estimate had an energy of {\$}2.6\backslashtimes10{\^{}}{\{}34{\}}{\$} erg. In contrast, we detect no white light flares down to an energy limit of {\$}2\backslashtimes10{\^{}}{\{}30{\}}{\$} erg in the nearby L{\$}5\backslashgamma{\$} brown dwarf 2M0355+11, a member of the 150-Myr old AB Dor Moving Group. This is consistent with the view that fast magnetic reconnection is suppressed in cool atmospheres. We discuss two complex, multi-peaked flares observed in 2M0335+23 and compare them to complex flares observed on warmer stars. We argue that these complex flares can be understood as sympathetic flares, in which fast-mode MHD waves similar to EUV waves in t